title: For Sale:  RCBS .223/5.56x45 SB T/C Die Set w/ Extras
postcontent: Deal of the week for a reloader.  The pics show it all but more than just the die set I'm including a spare primer removal shaft, 4 spare primer removal pins, a RCBS #10 shell holder and a sample-size container of Imperial Sizing Die Wax. Together the worth is well over $50 but I have used it twice in my Dillon 500RL so technically it is no longer "new" so pricing it accordingly.   Here is a little description detailing the selling points of this setup. First paid = first owned. Local pickup available only at a either my home or a location of your choosing.  The RCBS AR Series die set is a must for any progressive reloader. Each set comes packaged with a full length small base sizing die and a taper crimp seating die. With this combination reloading for an AR-style, semi-automatic, pump action or lever action rifle just became a lot easier. Small base sizing dies size brass to minimum specifications and help to ensure that cartridges will chamber every time. The taper crimp seating die is helpful as it is a bit more forgiving die for crimping cases that have variable case lengths; helping to reduce the number of bulges and buckled shoulders when crimping in bullets with a cannelure. Due to the fact that this product sizes more than regular dies, it is crucial to have a sufficient amount of high quality lubricant to prevent stuck cases. These dies will also work with any single stage or turret press that will accept 7/8"-14 threaded dies, Shellholder sold separately.  RCBS® AR Series Die Sets are a must for progressive reloaders. They feature a Small Base Sizer Die designed for semi-automatic firearms, and a Taper Crimp Seater Die. The Small Base Sizer guarantees the cartridge will rechamber in AR-platform weapons.

title: For Sale:  WW2 GERMAN MG15 WATER COOLED MG NAZI LUFTWAFFE EAGLE/2 MARKED
postcontent: WW2 German ground-crews MG.15 Water-cooled machinegun. Most of these were used by SS and Luftwaffe field-division units during 1941-45. The Luftwaffe started phasing out Mg.15s out of Long-range bombers and JU87s in late 1940 to be replaced with Mg.181s. Mg.15s still serviceable found their way to ground-service conversions. Some found their way initially to DAK units and later to SS and Foreign-volunteer Divisions in the Eastern front as weapons demands began to place a toll. This is one of such machineguns. Originally designed by Kreighoff and manufactured by Rheinmetall, Borsig A.G. They were marked St.61 on all receivers ( MG.15 export code) to initially be sent as military-Aid to Hungary, Romania and other Axis-allied countries. As the tides of war began to reverse, SS and Wehrmacht troops put these in service. All Mg.15s pulled from Luftwaffe service were sent to MAS in France and redesigned for ground-role with the addition of a water jacket and new barrel bushings in 1942 and sent to the Eeastern front.Excellent condition overall, with undented water jacket, and the correct, shortened Mg.34 bipod. Luftwaffe nazi " Eagle/over/2" marked on the right side of the trigger guard, on the trigger, on the cocking lever, on the magazine lock, on the sustained-fire button, on the front sight and on a few other places. A very interesting water-cooled variant, complete with elevated sights, huge water jacket and original bipod. Brass plug still in place. RARE bakelit housing. This is a demilitarized nazi MG, with a dummy receiver. Bolt pulls back, locks and slides forward. Amazing display, legal to own as it is considered a non-firearm, thus NO FFL or special license required. Completely legal to own.$2450 + 65 shipp.
